<a name="arret_de_la_traduction_qui_a_ete_effectuee"></a><h2> Arrêt de la traduction qui a été effectuée :  </h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
<a href="http://domainename.com/divers/shuttleworth_slashdot_4_avril_2005.html" class="urlextern" title="http://domainename.com/divers/shuttleworth_slashdot_4_avril_2005.html" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://domainename.com/divers/shuttleworth_slashdot_4_avril_2005.html</a>
</p>

<p>
Si vous voulez réagir : <a href="http://forum.ubuntu-fr.org/viewtopic.php?id=2805" class="urlextern" title="http://forum.ubuntu-fr.org/viewtopic.php?id=2805" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://forum.ubuntu-fr.org/viewtopic.php?id=2805</a>
</p>

<p>
 A long, long time ago, you asked questions of Mark Shuttleworth &ndash; astronaut, entrepreneur, activist, and now chief of Debian-and-GNOME based distribution Ubuntu Linux. Mark&rsquo;s been understandably busy running the world of Ubuntu, especially considering the imminent release of the group&rsquo;s newest version, Hoary Hedgehog. He&rsquo;s answered below questions on everything from what makes it worth paying for a trip to space to how software offered with source, for free, and under a liberal license (aka Free software) can sustain itself and its creators. Read on for his answers. 
</p>
<hr noshade="noshade" size="1" />

<p>
Il y a très, très longtemps, vous avez posé des questions à Mark Shuttleworth &ndash; astronaute, entrepreneur, activiste et maintenant à la tête de la distribution Ubuntu Linux basée sur Debian et GNOME. On peut aisément comprendre que Mark ait été très occupé à faire fonctionner le monde d&rsquo;Ubuntu, surtout si l&rsquo;on prend en compte la sortie imminente de la nouvelle version préparée par le groupe, nom de code &ldquo;Hoary Hedgehog&rdquo;. Mark a répondu à des questions aussi diverses que &ldquo;est-ce que ça vaut le coup de dépenser de l&rsquo;argent pour faire un voyage dans l&rsquo;espace&rdquo; ou encore &ldquo;comment des logiciels gratuits, distribués avec leurs code source et placés sous des licences permissives, peuvent perdurer et faire vivre leurs créateurs&rdquo;. Lisez la suite pour ses réponses.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [1-1587] -->
<a name="ubuntu_target_is"></a><h1> Ubuntu target is... ? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 I&rsquo;m curious who you see as the Ubuntu target user/audience. It seems that from the ease of use, and &ldquo;price&rdquo;, that you are trying to target the audience that doesn&rsquo;t care for Microsoft, or that is trying to do things and can&rsquo;t afford Microsoft.
</p>

<p>
With that, I&rsquo;m a little curious as to why Ubuntu has chosen Gnome as the desktop? On older machines (such as my HP Kayak), Ubuntu runs passingly well, but simply having an option that probes the machine and then picks a desktop like XFCE or IceWM using a similar theme to the Gnome one would help refurbished/recycled machines really shine.
</p>

<p>
Similarly, it would seem that there are some software choices that could be tuned as well. As much as I like to use Open Office on my newer machines, selecting a more modest office offering for lower specification machines seems like a reasonable option.
</p>

<p>
Interested in your thoughts on this... Mark Shuttleworth: The Ubuntu project is all about creating a free, high quality <acronym title="Operating System">OS</acronym> for everybody &ndash; home, office and data center. So we&rsquo;ve tried to choose the best mix of desktop apps in terms of functionality and compatibility rather than optimising for low-end hardware. So, off the single install CD, you get a Gnome desktop with Firefox, OpenOffice, Gstreamer for multimedia and other well-known favourites. We include some other favourites on the <acronym title="International Organization for Standardization">ISO</acronym>, like Thunderbird, as well as the most popular server apps (Apache, Samba etc) so that they are all available without having to go to the network during the install.
</p>

<p>
Pretty much everything else in the known universe is available off the network archives, so you can apt-get anything that would also be in Debian or an many of the other independent repositories that have .deb packages, we bring them all together in our network repository so it&rsquo;s easy to find and install almost anything that won&rsquo;t send you to jail.
</p>

<p>
It&rsquo;s hard to pick favourites, but as Thom May blogged this week, it&rsquo;s not something one can avoid. One of the nice consequences of working in the open source world is that people have taken matters into their own hands, have picked their own favourites and are working on Kubuntu (Ubuntu but with a KDE desktop default install). It should be released with KDE 3.4 on April 6, the same day we release Ubuntu with Gnome 2.10, and will rock.
</p>

<p>
I&rsquo;m keen to see an XFCE-buntu too, so come along to #ubuntu-devel or #kubuntu on irc.freenode.net if you&rsquo;d like to work on that. I&rsquo;m also keen to see flavours of Ubuntu that are tuned for LTSP or embedded environments. And some folks were talking about Enlightenment E17 on Ubuntu too, so we may see a bunch of these flavours emerge for our next release, its up to the Ubuntu community. Ubuntu is, and always will be, entirely FREE in every sense, so it&rsquo;s a perfect playground for people to build on and innovate with.
</p>
<hr noshade="noshade" size="1" />

</div>
<!-- SECTION [1588-4449] -->
<a name="la_cible_d_ubuntu_est"></a><h1> La cible d'Ubuntu est... ? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 Je suis curieux de savoir quel public/utilisateur cible vous voyez pour Ubuntu. Il semble d&rsquo;après la simplicité d&rsquo;utilisation, et le “prix”, que vous tentez de viser le public qui n&rsquo;a que faire de Microsoft, ou ceux qui essaient de faire des choses et ne peuvent pas accéder à Microsoft.
</p>

<p>
En plus de cela, je suis un peu curieux de savoir pourquoi Ubuntu a choisi Gnome comme bureau? Sur des machines anciennes (telles que mon HP Kayak), Ubuntu fonctionnne étonnamment bien, mais avoir simplement une option qui teste la machine et sélectionne un bureau tel XFCE ou IceWM en utilisant un thème  semblable à celui de Gnome pourrait aider à vraiment mettre en valeur des machines mises au rebut/recyclées.
</p>

<p>
De même, il semblerait que les choix logiciels pourraient aussi être affinés. Pour autant que j&rsquo;aime utiliser Open Office sur mes machines récentes, le choix d&rsquo;une suite bureautique plus modeste pour des machines aux capacités réduites semble une option raisonnable.
</p>

<p>
Intéressé par vos idées… Mark Shuttleworth: Tout l&rsquo;objectif du projet Ubuntu est de créer un SE libre et de grande qualité pour tout le monde - la maison, le bureau et les centres de données. Nous avons donc essayé de choisir le meilleur mélange d&rsquo;applications de bureau en termes de fonctionnalité et compatibilité plutôt que d&rsquo;optimiser pour le matériel peu performant. Depuis l&rsquo;unique CD d&rsquo;installation, vous avez un bureau Gnome avec Firefox, OpenOffice, Gstreamer pour le multimédia ainsi que d&rsquo;autres favoris bien connus. Nous incluons aussi d&rsquo;autres favoris dans l&rsquo;<acronym title="International Organization for Standardization">ISO</acronym>, comme Thunderbird, ou encore les applications serveur les plus populaires (Apache, Samba etc) afin que toutes soient  disponibles sans avoir à aller sur le réseau pendant l&rsquo;installation.
</p>

<p>
Presque tout ce qu&rsquo;il existe d&rsquo;autre dans l&rsquo;univers connu est disponible depuis les archives réseau, afin que vous puissiez apt-prendre <a href="#fn1" name="fnt1" class="fn_top">1)</a> tout ce qui serait déjà dans Debian ou l&rsquo;un des nombreux autres dépôts indépendants qui ont des paquets .deb, nous les centralisons tous dans notre dépôt réseau afin qu&rsquo;il soit facile de trouver et installer quasiment tout ce qui ne vous mènera pas en prison.
</p>

<p>
Il est difficile de choisir ses favoris, mais comme l&rsquo;a bloggué Thom May cette semaine, on ne peut y échapper. Une des conséquences intéressantes que de travailler dans le monde de l&rsquo;open-source est que les gens ont pu prendre les choses en main, choisir leurs propres favoris et travaillent sur Kubuntu (Ubuntu mais avec KDE installé par défaut). Kubuntu devrait sortir le 6 avril prochain, avec KDE 3.4, le même jour que la sortie de Hoary, équipée de Gnome 2.10, et ça va tuer.
</p>

<p>
Je suis aussi enthousiaste de voir un XFCE-buntu donc venez sur #ubuntu-devel ou #kubuntu sur irc.freenode.net si vous voulez travailler la-dessus. Je suis aussi enthousiaste de voir des dérivés d&rsquo;Ubuntu optimisées pour LTSP ou l&rsquo;embarqué. Certains parlaient aussi de Enlightenment E17 sur Ubuntu, on devrait donc voir apparaître un paquet de ces dérivés pour notre prochaine sortie; cela ne dépend que de la communauté Ubuntu. Ubuntu est et restera toujours LIBRE et GRATUIT <a href="#fn2" name="fnt2" class="fn_top">2)</a>, c&rsquo;est donc un terrain privilégié pour créer et innover.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [4450-7862] -->
<a name="what_s_so_special_about_ubuntu"></a><h1> What's so special about Ubuntu? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 This is a question that&rsquo;s sure to come up in many different ways, but I&rsquo;d really like to know what is so special about Ubuntu that its purposes could not be as well served by contributing to the Debian tree? I&rsquo;m assuming you have your reasons &ndash; is it about having control of the packaging, more frequent releases, what? Do you see Ubunutu supplanting Debian someday, or will it just be a branded form of the more open Debian (akin to Fedora/Redhat)?
</p>

<p>
Also, becoming aware of your financial resources, I can&rsquo;t help but wonder whether Ubuntu is intended to be a money maker, or it seen as a gift to the community?
</p>

<p>
(My new Athlon 64 system is coming any day now, and I&rsquo;ve decided to try Ubuntu first. So far, it looks very nice from afar.) <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Well, I hope your Ubuntu amd64 system has been working very well since you posed the question, and you&rsquo;re ready to update to Hoary Hedgehog after it releases [this] month <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" />
</p>

<p>
Ubuntu won&rsquo;t replace Debian. If people love it&rsquo;s Ubuntu, it&rsquo;s because it&rsquo;s built on such great engineering. Debian/sid is an awesome asset to the world of free software, even if it is the boy that breaks your toys.
</p>

<p>
The Ubuntu team takes Sid, every six months, and makes a secure, tested, and supported release of it. Hopefully many of the patches (published continuously at <a href="http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/" class="urlextern" title="http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/</a> but don&rsquo;t let Scott tell you he personally made all of those patches <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" /> we make in the process are adopted by the Debian maintainers, so Sid gets better as a result of Ubuntu, it is designed to be a two-way street.
</p>

<p>
Then, hopefully, people take that regular, predictable release and do awesome things like Kubuntu and GuadaLinex with it.
</p>

<p>
Over time there may be some ongoing areas where we take a different route to Debian because of different priorities and scheduling, like X.org, Gnome 2.10 and possibly OpenOffice.org2 in Hoary, and that&rsquo;s why we are investing in Bazaar and baz-ng, the free/libre revision control system that I hope will make it easy for us to share code with upstream and other distros in a sane fashion.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [7863-9974] -->
<a name="qu_a_ubuntu_de_tellement_special"></a><h1> Qu'a Ubuntu de tellement spécial? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 C&rsquo;est une question <strong>qui doit revenir régulièrement</strong>(?), mais j&rsquo;aimerais vraiment savoir ce qu&rsquo;il y a de si spécial dans Ubuntu, qui fait que son objectif ne peut pas être atteint en contribuant à Debian? Je suppose que vous avez vos raisons &ndash; garder le contrôle sur le <strong>packaging</strong>, faire des <strong>releases</strong> plus régulièrement, ou bien? Pensez-vous que Ubuntu prendra la place de Debian un jour, ou s&rsquo;agit-il d&rsquo;une version plus <strong>marketing</strong>(?) de Debian (<strong>akin to Fedora Redhat</strong>)?
</p>

<p>
Etant conscient de vos resources financières, je ne peux que me demander si Ubuntu est destiné à produire de l&rsquo;argent, ou si elle doit être vue comme un don à la communauté?
</p>

<p>
(Mon nouvel Athlon 64 devrait arriver d&rsquo;un jour à l&rsquo;autre maintenant, et j&rsquo;ai décidé d&rsquo;essayer Ubuntu en premier. Ca a l&rsquo;air très sympa au premier abord) <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Eh bien, j&rsquo;espère que votre Ubutuntu amd64 fonctionne bien, étant donné que vous avez posé la question, et que vous êtes prêt à mettre à jour votre système en Hoary dès sa release ce mois-ci <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" />
</p>

<p>
Ubuntu ne remplacera pas Debian. Si les gens aiment leur Ubuntu, c&rsquo;est car il est basé sur un si excellent système. Debian/sid est un excellent élément du monde du logiciel libre, même si c&rsquo;est un peu le genre de gamin qui casse vos jouets.
</p>

<p>
L&rsquo;équipe d&rsquo;Ubuntu prend Sid, tous les six mois, et en réalise une <strong>release</strong> sécurisée, testée, et <strong>supported</strong>(?). Une bonne partie des patchs (publiés en continu sur <a href="http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/" class="urlextern" title="http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://people.ubuntu.com/~scott/patches/</a> - mais ne laissez pas Scott vous dire qu&rsquo;il a fait lui même tous ces patchs <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" /> ) que nous réalisons sont récupérés par les mainteneurs Debian, ainsi Sid s&rsquo;améliore grâce à Ubuntu - les 2 partis sont gagnants.
</p>

<p>
Ainsi, il est possible de prendre cette release régulièrement et de manière planifiée, afin de réaliser des trucs super tels que Kubuntu ou encore GuadaLinex.
</p>

<p>
Au fil du temps, il est possible que <strong>différents éléments</strong> nous fassent prendre une route différente de Debian, en raison de priorités différentes <strong>scheduling?</strong>, comme X.org, Gnome 2.10 et éventuellement OpenOffice.org2 dans Hoary, et c&rsquo;est pour cela que <strong>nous nous lancons</strong> dans Bazaar et Baz-ng, le système de révision libre qui, je l&rsquo;espère, nous facilitera le partage de code avec d&rsquo;autres distributions (<strong>upstream?</strong>) (<strong>in a sane fashion?</strong>).
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [9975-12383] -->
<a name="debian_packages"></a><h1> Debian packages </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 I read that you guys are rebuilding your own version of all the debian packages you use instead of using vanilla debian. Apparently this means that Ubuntu will not work with general debian apt repositories. Is this true? If so, what is the reasoning behind this and will you in the future be considering changing this policy? <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Yes, we import every package from Debian as well as .deb packages from a lot of other sources that you can find on apt-get.org. So if you enable the &ldquo;universe&rdquo; and &ldquo;multiverse&rdquo; repositories in your /etc/apt/sources.list file on an Ubuntu system you immediately see everything that you would find in Sid, and most anything else in deb format too, in one shot.
</p>

<p>
This allows us to reduce the time people spend looking for backports and packages, and to ensure that they actually all build from source at release time. it also allows us, if we get time, to create some sanity in library version dependencies across all 16,000 packages.
</p>

<p>
Our core team focuses its attention on the server and core desktop apps (in &ldquo;main&rdquo;), and then a separate team called the Masters of the Universe (an inside joke) manages everything in universe and multiverse. That team&rsquo;s work on KDE packages resulted in KDE being moved into main, and the creation of Kubuntu for our next release in April. If you&rsquo;re interested in bringing even more packages into universe or multiverse, join #ubuntu-motu.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [12384-13818] -->
<a name="les_paquets_debian"></a><h1> Les paquets Debian </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 J&rsquo;ai lu que vous êtes en train de reconstruire vos propres versions de tous les paquets Debian au lieu d&rsquo;utiliser les paquets vanilia debian. Cela veut apparemment dire que  les paquets des ressources debian ne seront pas compatibles. Est-ce vrai ? Si tel est le cas, est-ce un choix et pourra-t-il changer dans le futur? <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Oui, nous importons tous les paquets debian comme des paquets .deb de multiples sources que vous pouvez trouver sur apt-get.org. Donc, si vous autorisez les dépôts &ldquo;universe&rdquo; et &ldquo;multiverse&rdquo; dans votre fichier /etc/apt/sources.list sur votre système Ubuntu vous trouverez tout ce qui se trouve dans les paquets &ldquo;Sid&rdquo;, et à peu près tout ce qui existe en format .deb, dans le même temps.
</p>

<p>
Ca nous permet de réduire le temps que les gens passent pour les backports et les paquets, et cela assure qu&rsquo;ils sont en fait tous construits à partir des sources. Ca nous permet aussi, si nous avons le temps, de créer une certaine homogénéité dans les librairies de dépendances entre environl 16,000 paquets.
</p>

<p>
Notre noyau dur se centre sur le serveur et les applications du bureau (dans &ldquo;main&rdquo;), et l&rsquo;équipe de &ldquo;Maîtres de l&rsquo;Univers&rdquo;  (une blague interne) gère &ldquo;universe&rdquo; et &ldquo;multiverse&rdquo;. Cette équipe travaille sur les paquets KDE entrainant le passage de KDE dans le &ldquo;main&rdquo;, et la création de Kubuntu sortie prévue en avril. Si vous avez envie de fournir des paquets différents dan &ldquo;universe&rdquo; ou &ldquo;multiverse&rdquo;, rejoignez #ubuntu-motu.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [13819-15325] -->
<a name="modifications"></a><h1> Modifications </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 After I installed your distro recently, I was impressed by the attention to graphical detail. The gdm login screen, the default theme and the wallpapers chosen for the desktop were all very nice.
</p>

<p>
One thing that stood out was the choice to eliminate desktop icons and change the required trash icon into a panel applet. Why was this choice made? <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Because I&rsquo;m the SABDFL &ndash; and a Virgo? It just seemed like the Right Thing to do, in keeping with the Ubuntu philosophy of keeping it simple and making it Just Work. A user is free to clutter up her own desktop as much as she likes, we shouldn&rsquo;t be doing that for her <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" />
</p>

<p>
That doesn&rsquo;t mean it wasn&rsquo;t quite a debate at our Oxford conference last year... and I guess we&rsquo;ll be having similar debates at our Sydney community conf in late April, where we&rsquo;ll be laying out the roadmap for Breezy Badger, our October release.
</p>

<p>
Making the desktop efficient and great to use is a lot of fun. If you have stong thoughts on the subject, come along to Sydney or another Ubuntu conf and join the debate.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [15326-16397] -->
<a name="corporate_usage"></a><h1> Corporate Usage </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
 I&rsquo;ve been a Red Hat/Fedora user for years now, but I decided to give Ubuntu a try, as it had some of the most recent packages included (Gnome 2.8 and Evolution 2.0) by default. Needless to say, I was very impressed by the polish of a pre-release version, and I have switched my workstations at work, and my Linux boxes at home over to Ubuntu.
</p>

<p>
I was, however, disappointed by the lack of &ldquo;corporate&rdquo; tools currently included with Ubuntu. All of our client machines here are currently running Fedora with a customized install script written using kickstart, so when a machine dies,I can pop in the custom install CD and have a blank machine back on the network in 5 or 10 minutes. Are there are plans to include kickstart-like features and NIS support inside of Ubuntu&rsquo;s installation routines? I would switch our entire company over to Ubuntu in a flash if that were the case. I&rsquo;m sure other companies would enjoy seeing the addition of such features as well. <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: Hoary Hedgehog, due April 6th, will have kickstart support thanks to the great work of Colin Watson. I can&rsquo;t speak to NIS, if it&rsquo;s something we could integrate cleanly and elegantly then put a specification together on the Ubuntu wiki at <a href="http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/" class="urlextern" title="http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/</a> and link to it from the BOF planning page at <a href="http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/UbuntuDownUnderBOFs" class="urlextern" title="http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/UbuntuDownUnderBOFs" onclick="return svchk()" onkeypress="return svchk()" rel="nofollow">http://www.ubuntulinux.org/wiki/UbuntuDownUnderBOFs</a> &ndash; then we&rsquo;ll discuss implementing it for Breezy Badger.
</p>

<p>
Ubuntu should be great in a corporate environment. We will never include proprietary tools like CodeWeavers, but it&rsquo;s just a matter of time before someone creates an Ubuntu derivative that includes those too.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [16398-18027] -->
<a name="how_do_you_get_support_for_the_less_popular_work"></a><h1> How do you get support for the less popular work? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
Hi Mark, as with any (F)<acronym title="Open Source Software">OSS</acronym> project you&rsquo;re almost entirely depending on volunteers. That&rsquo;s OK for popular projects, but to work on, say, an admin or accounting back-end someone still needs to do the heavy lifting without the promise of the kind of glamour and street cred that the likes of Firefox offer.
</p>

<p>
Have you found a way to get support for the less sexy projects and if so, how? <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: I wish there was a good answer to this. There are so many wonderful things that open source could achieve in the world if we could draw talent to less sexy projects.
</p>

<p>
For example, I&rsquo;ve been funding work on SchoolTool for two years now, and we&rsquo;re only JUST starting to see a community forming around it. I think the answer is that open source depends on having some core working product to work with in the first place &ndash; it&rsquo;s very difficult to sustain a community unless the tool is already in widespread production use.
</p>

<p>
To get from the concept to that point requires either an individual with the skills and passion and energy and time to build it, singlehandedly, or funding from philanthropy or commercial interests.
</p>

<p>
Another thing I&rsquo;d like to see are open source administration systems for government &ndash; local councils all around the world have the same problems, they should be using the same tools and sharing them freely. Then Kinshasa and Paris could both benefit from open source. But YOU try motivate someone to hack on a sewerage management system in their spare time.
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [18028-19564] -->
<a name="what_do_you_think_of_this_idea"></a><h1> What do you think of this idea? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
I switch from distro to distro whenever I find one that is better than the current one. I just moved from Slackware (with dropline gnome) to Ubuntu because of the latest gnome and kernel. My brother is so impressed with Ubuntu that he&rsquo;s switching from Windows. Well he&rsquo;s also partly unimpressed with Windows security. He&rsquo;s currently backing everything up and the transfer of files and all is rather tedious. We thought of an idea to make the process faster and would like your opinion on it.
</p>

<p>
Would it be possible to have an Ubuntu install CD which checks a Windows or Linux installation, migrates its users/files and &ldquo;converts&rdquo; their system to Ubuntu? I realize there are some hurdles to overcome this in the Windows world but it seems feasible from one distro to the next. What do you think of the idea?
</p>

<p>
Thanks in advance. <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: I think that&rsquo;s a great idea! With Gnu Parted reaching the point where I might trust it to resize my Grandma&rsquo;s NTFS partition and create a new ext3 partition for Ubuntu, the next step will be to move as much of her data into the new Linux partition in a sane way, as possible.
</p>

<p>
There&rsquo;s low-hanging fruit that you could pick, like desktop backgrounds, fonts, home directories and other useful stuff which could be moved across to preserve her working environment and keep it as familiar as possible.
</p>

<p>
Good luck!
</p>

</div>
<!-- SECTION [19565-20953] -->
<a name="everything_free_--_what_s_the_business_plan"></a><h1> Everything free -- what's the business plan? </h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
How does Canonical plan on making money? Ubuntu seems to be completely and utterly free, in both senses of the word. In my mind at least, the &lsquo;services will pay for development&rsquo; business plan for Free Software went out of style when the dot-com bubble burst. How will your company be different? <acronym title="Microsoft">MS</acronym>: You&rsquo;re right that the &ldquo;services pay for development&rdquo; model is unlikely to work very well for single applications. An entire distribution, though, is slightly different, because the number of users is potentially much, much greater than the number of users for, say, a web server or database app.
</p>

<p>
Canonical provides support for Ubuntu, but more importantly we provide support for companies that provide support for Ubuntu. The idea is to create an ecosystem of people who collaborate on the free software. You can see the beginnings of that ecosystem on this page of Ubuntu service providers, and I hope it will continue grow as fast as it has since Warty hit the streets.
</p>

<p>
Part of being sustainable is keeping the costs down, so we focus resources on development and support, not marketing or office waste. The guys will tell you I&rsquo;m a cheap bastard when it comes to the frills (Canonical One doesn&rsquo;t *actually* belong to Canonical <img src="/smileys/icon_smile.gif" align="middle" alt=":-)" />.
</p>

<p>
I&rsquo;d very much like to make the distro project sustainable, because I&rsquo;ve never had the privilege to work with such talented guys who work as hard as this team, and they deserve to be rewarded and to know that people appreciate the value they add every day. If it doesn&rsquo;t work utthat way, though, I&rsquo;m honoured to consider it a gift back to the open source world, which played such a critical role in helping me build Thawte. So I hope it&rsquo;s commerce, though it may turn out to be philanthropy. Either way, it&rsquo;s still cheaper than going back to space, or hooking up with fast planes/boats/women, which I supposed would be Plan B.
</p>

</div>
